80, von Heyking shows how these materials helped shape the ways in which Albertans have identified themselves and their place in the world around them. The complex process of curriculum development is also explored; by clarifying how the framework of decision-making regarding school content was created, von Heyking provides valuable insights into current debates about the purpose and content of public education. By tracing the evolution of this curriculum over the course of seventy-five years, Creating Citizens gives the reader a unique opportunity to analyze the images of the nation and the region as they were taught to generations of Alberta schoolchildren.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEducationxCurriculazAlbertaxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh  aalberta curriculum changes.  aalberta curriculum development.  aalberta curriculum overview.  aalberta curriculum.  acanadian citizenship.  acitizenship.  acreating canadian citizenship.  aeducation in alberta.  aeducation in canada.  agovernment and schools.  ahistory of education.  ahistory of social studies.  aidentity creation.  aschools and identity.  asocial studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552383209?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552383209423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552383209/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles